Malaria Detection: A Deep Learning Approach¶

by: Nicols Salazar Beltrn (nicolas-salbe.github.io)

Problem Definition¶

Context¶

Although preventable and curable, malaria cases have steadily increased in the past decades. According to the WHO, there were an alarming estimated 247 million cases of malaria in 2021 worldwide. The vast majority of these cases are found in underdeveloped tropical countries where socioeconomic conditions make malaria prevention and treatment a significant challenge.
Regarding treatment, early diagnosis of malaria leads to reduced disease severity, death prevention and lower transmission rates. Parasitological diagnosis of malaria relies on light microscopy or immunochromatographic RDTs (Rapid Diagnostic Testing). Particularly, light microscopy requires professional inspection of infected blood cells performed by a microscopist who may not be widely present in malaria-affected regions and may not be able to effectively handle large amount of samples.
Supporting early detection of malaria through an automated diagnosis system would specially benefit vulnerable populations that have limited access to healthcare and would help better channeling treatment efforts and resources.
One such system could be based on a Deep Learning classifier that can repeatability and accurately process microscopy images to determine whether the sample is infected by the malaria parasite or not.
Sources:
WHO1, WHO2, WHO3

Objectives¶

The objective of this project is to develop a Deep Learning model that can support malaria diagnosis by classifying red blood cells microscopy images as coming from a parasitized or an uninfected sample.

Key questions¶

  • How well can the developed model tell the difference between a parasitized and an uninfected cells?
  • How many of the blood samples classified as parasitized are actually parasitized?
  • How many of the blood samples classified as uninfected are actually parasitized?

Problem formulation¶

The data science problem addressed by this project is to build a CNN model that can detect patterns in a dataset of labeled red blood images and can learn how to classify unseen images as coming from a parasitized or an unifected blood sample.

Data Description ¶

There are a total of 24,958 train and 2,600 test images (colored) that we have taken from microscopic images. These images are of the following categories:

Parasitized: The parasitized cells contain the Plasmodium parasite which causes malaria
Uninfected: The uninfected cells are free of the Plasmodium parasites

The extracted folder has different folders for train and test data will contain the different sizes of images for parasitized and uninfected cells within the respective folder name.

The size of all images must be the same and should be converted to 4D arrays so that they can be used as an input for the convolutional neural network. Also, we need to create the labels for both types of images to be able to train and test the model.

Let's do the same for the training data first and then we will use the same code for the test data as well.

['cell_images/train/uninfected',
 'cell_images/train/parasitized',
 'cell_images/test/uninfected',
 'cell_images/test/parasitized']

Before resizing let's get a picture of how different image sizes are among the dataset:

  • Image size across the dataset is quite diverse although most of these sizes are larger than 120x120 pixels.
  • It is not explicitly required in this notebook but the project's FAQ indicates that all images should be resized to 64x64 pixels. This new size seems to be a good trade-off for staying close to the aspect ratio of the original images.

For this binary classification problem we will use the following labels:

  • 1: parasitized
  • 0: uninfected

Data Exploration¶

Let's visualize the images from the train data

Observations and insights:¶

  • Cells images show different forms and colors
  • Parasitized cells show a sort of stains in random positions
  • Uninfected cells show a uniform color across their area
  • A model that can learn color patterns, more than shape patterns, will likely be able to perform well

Converting RGB to HSV of Images using OpenCV¶

HSV (Hue Saturation Value) is a colorspace that is better suited than RGB to handle color characteristics of images.

RGB images from our processed arrays cannot be directly converted into HSV arrays because OpenCV expects the images to be in BRG format for correct conversion. Let's then first open the original images of the dataset in BRG and then convert them to HSV.

Processing Images using Gaussian Blurring¶

Gaussian blurring is an image processing method that smoothes out large pixel variations such that the resulting image seems to be blur. This helps removing source image noise for some applications.

Gaussian Blurring on test data¶

Think About It: Would blurring help us for this problem statement in any way? What else can we try?

  • Gaussian blurring is not useful for this application because the target pattern to highlight is color rather than shape
  • A more useful filter could be a contrast filter that can enhance the color differences in a cell

Fit and train our Model

Kera's fit method extracts the validation data by taking the last validation_split portion of the input data. Since our training arrays are ordered by class in almost equal parts, passing these arrays to fit would lead to validating only on the uninfected cell images.
This is unconvenient as both the validation AND the training processes will be biased.

Evaluating the model¶

82/82 [==============================] - 1s 5ms/step - loss: 0.0508 - accuracy: 0.9800

Test accuracy of cnn_model_2:  0.98

Observations and insights:¶

  • The validation accuracy shows a slight oscillating behavior probably due to the Batch Normalization causing some overshoot when trying to normalize the trained parameters in the layers of the fully connected network. As epochs increase the validation accuracy seems to settle down but it actually keeps on having some ripple.
  • LeakyReLU does not help either to improve the overall accuracy of the model. For this relatively shallow network, the effect of sparsity achieved by ReLU in cnn_model_1 seems to be more beneficial.
  • There's no apparent benefit of using BatchNormalization as the model is stil overfitting slightly and there's no significant improvement in the computation time.

Visualizing Augmented images¶

Observations and insights:¶

  • Parasitized cells show a stain pattern in which color is more relevant than shape. Therefore, augmenting the data with flips or rotations may not be beneficial as the CNN won't give much weight to shape patterns anyways.
  • Applying a zoom in transformation is not recommended as the stain pattern may remain out of scope and the CNN could get confused.
  • Applying some sort of color contrast transformation could be helpful instead. However, when using the brightnees_range parameter the images turned out to be all black.

Final Model Selection¶

test recall (parasitized) 0.9569 0.9938 0.9885 0.9962 0.9592

Several models and techniques have been used in this project to address the malaria detection problem. The CNN models were built to experiment the possible improvements that architecture changes and learning techniques may achieve.
The above table compares the most relevant metrics for the different problems taking into detection performance but also complexity. The following conclusions can be drawn from the table:

  • Although extremely simple in terms of architecture, cnn_model_base is the most complex model as it required training more than 1 million parameters. This gives it better test accuracies than deeper models such as cnn_model_4 but at the price of overfitting and taking the risk of not performing as good with other unseen data.
  • The use of max pooling and droput in cnn_model_1 made this model cut the trainable parameters by one third despite being much deeper than cnn_model_base. The additional layers help to better detect underlying patterns and within a similar number of epochs as before, both the training and the validation accuracy settled down at around 98%. The resulting test accuracy is also 98% but more importantly the test recall for the parasitized class is > 99%.
  • Contrarily to what was expected, cnn_model_2 showed a greater difference between training and validation test accuracies than cnn_model_1. Introducing batch normalization caused some oscillations in the validation accuracy and LeakyRELU didn't benefit the overall occuracy.
  • As expected, having the same architecture as cnn_model_1, cnn_model_3 had a very similar performance with the augmented data but at higher computation power price. Most likely, if the dataset fed into this model was expanded the performance could continue increasing.
  • Not needing to train the parameters of convolutional layers is very convenient and makes cnn_model_4 the simpler model to train. However, the architecture of the last block of VGG16 doesn't benefit much this application, yielding the lowest perfomance among all the models.

Some other models could be added to this table that could bring some improvements. Some examples are:

  • Use HSV images to feed cnn_model_1: providing images with better color contrast can make the stain pattern common in the parasitized be easier to extract
  • Use expanded data augmented dataset: increase the numer of samples in the original dataset to improve accuracy
  • Use pre-trained models that are known to perform well when detecting color patterns

The chosen model: cnn_model_1¶

Out of the 5 CNN models presented in this notebook, cnn_mode_1 is the best model for the following reasons:

  • Simplicity: It achieves an overall test accuracy of more than 98% with only 3 convolutional layers and 3 fully connected layers, making it quick to train.
  • Efficient: With a few trainable parameters it is able to extract the most important features and combine them in such a way that it can accurately detect malaria patterns in the cells images.
  • High recall: In this application, the recall to detect a parasitized cell is the most important score as it indicates how many actual parisizited cells the model is expected to classify as uninfected. This is critical because it is preferable to treat for malaria someone who is actually uninfected rather than leaving someone who does have malaria untreated. With a recall > 99%, cnn_model_1 would misdiagnose less than 1 person every 100 of being uninfected when actually parasitized.
  • High accuracy: when classifying unseen cell images this model can give us overall around 98% confidence that the resulting prediction is correct.

Model cnn_model_1 performs well because it abstracts away the location of the parasitized stain pattern disregarding a specific shape and rather focusing on color. This feature extraction is possible thanks to the 3 convolutional layers and the max pooling done after each of them. Once the right features are available at the flatten layer, then the 3 fully connected layers with dropout learn the right combinations that minimize the loss function.

The model may be further improved by training it on a larger dataset, trying differents optimizers that can avoid local minima, and exploring on architectures that can enhance color pattern feauture extraction.

Since for this application, as explained before, recall is more critical than precision, keeping cnn_model_1 is therefore preferable.

Executive Summary¶

A classifier model is proposed to support malaria diagnosis by predicting infection from microscopy images of parasitized red blood cells. The model consists of a 6-layer Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) that classifies a cell image sample as parasitized or uninfected. With the available dataset, the model was found to be able to differentiate parasitized from uninfected cells with an overall accuracy of around 98%, while yielding a >99% confidence that the cells classified as uninfected are not parasitized cells.
Although the performance of the model is quite good, further validation is required to ensure results are trustworthy. Using the model entails some limitations and risks such as reduced performance on unseen images processed differently than the training dataset.
If a digital microscopy-based diagnosis system is already in place, integration of the proposed model should be cost-effective and bring repeatability, accuracy, and scalability to the diagnosis workflow. Contrarily, if such system is not yet available its engineering costs should be weighted with the long-term economic and healthcare management benefits that it could bring.
Feedback from stakeholders such as healthcare authorities, governments and regulating bodies is required to further develop the proposed solution.

Problem and Solution Summary¶

Early diagnosis of malaria is critical to fight against a disease that keeps on threatening life and jeopardizing socioeconomic development in tropical regions where most of the cases are concentrated. Diagnostic testing of malaria through light microscopy requires inspection by a professional microscopist who may need to handle large amounts of samples in a repetitive and error-prone procedure. A method or tool that can automate this procedure may lead to more convenient and accurate diagnosis. As a result, limited healthcare resources can be better channeled.
The objective of this project was to build a CNN classifier model that can support microscopy-based malaria diagnosis by classifying unseen red blood cell images as coming from a parasitized or an uninfected blood sample.
The solution approach consisted in performing data exploration on the available dataset and iteratively building different CNN models based on the derived insights.
The dataset is formed by colored microscopy cell images of different sizes divided in ~25000 images for training the model and 2600 images for testing its performance. The images are almost equally distributed in samples of the parasitized and uninfected classes. The dataset images were all resized to be 64x64 pixels and normalized to the max pixel value.
Analysis of the RGB and HSV blood cell images revealed that parasitized cells show a particular color stain located in random positions and of varying shapes while uninfected cells are uniformly colored across their area. This suggested that a CNN that could learn such stain pattern would be able to perform well when classifying infected cells.
Several CNN architectures and training techniques were considered to explore model improvements in terms of performance and complexity. Metrics such as trainable parameters, training and validation accuracy, and test precision and recall, were assessed during the model iterations. Techniques such as normalization, data augmentation and tranfer learning were applied and evaluated too.
The chosen CNN model cnn_model_1 consists of 3 convolutional layers with ReLU activation and max pooling and 3 fully connected layers with ReLU and dropout regularization. The model was chosen because in comparison with the other models it is the one that best balances simplicity, efficiency, high recall, and high accuracy. With a simple architecture and few trainable parameters, the model is able to differentiate parasitized from uninfected cells with an overall accuracy of around 98%, while yielding a >99% confidence that the cells classified as uninfected are not parasitized cells.
Although further improvements and validation are required, implementing the proposed solution could make microscopy-based diagnosis of malaria much quicker, accurate and cheaper. This translates into earlier and more widespread diagnosis, resulting in better management of disease.

Recommendations for Implementation¶

As part of a microscopy-based malaria diagnosis system, the proposed CNN model may provide a valuable tool for healthcare professionals to more conveniently and accurately perform large malaria diagnosis campaigns in the most vulnerable areas where malaria is widespread. Blood samples are collected from people who are suspected to be infected, these samples are processed through light microscopy, and then the resulting blood cell images are fed to our CNN model which predicts whether the sample is parasitized or uninfected. The outcome of the classification process is communicated to the healthcare professional who then determines the right treatment for the affected person. This workflow may be repeated several times, but the accuracy of the cell classication step won't change. The whole process can be therefore less prone to errors, cheaper and be deployed more widely.
There are some risks and limitations in using our CNN model as a diagnostic tool:

  • the results obtained are related to tests done on 2600 samples images so there's a chance that the model doesn't generalize well on unseen images that differ too much from the original dataset
  • it implicitly classifies the cells as of one class or the other based on probability >50%. This may not be convenient as the margin for classification decision is small.
  • the model performs better on recall than on precision for classifying parasitized cells. Whether this is actually preferable or not should be consulted with a malaria treatment expert.
  • Cell images should be larger or equal than 64x64 pixels so that the preprocessing doesn't reduce the image quality and the classification result is not biased

Regarding the technical implementation and integration of the model itself, there are some important points to consider:

  • once trained, the model can be saved as hdf5 file and integrated in a pipeline for making predictions on images offline or online
  • the model can be part of the prediction algorithm of an integrated software that may run on a server accessible from a PC that also connects to the cell images database
  • the required computing power should be determined to properly run the model
  • there should also be some GUI or report generator that a healthcare professional can used to make a call on the diagnosis and the required treatment

Overall, considering a CNN solution to the malaria detection problem as presented here brings convenience in terms of repeatability, accuracy and potential scalability. These benefits need to be weighted with the engineering costs that integrating such solution may have and the long-term impact that it may represent in managing malaria in heavily affected areas.
